aphic name for a dweller by a woodland clearing or a meadow, from Middle English <i>ley</i> + <i>man</i>. Compare   Lee  .","English: nickname from <i>layman</i>, a word denoting an uneducated person.","Americanized form of German   Lehmann  ."]},{"name":"Leiman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Menashe, Shoshi, Yehoshua.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): from the Yiddish male personal name <i>Leyman</i>, of uncertain origin.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): metronymic from the Yiddish female personal name <i>Leye</i> (English <i>Leah</i>) + <i>man</i> ‘husband of’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":13,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Lyman was born in 1202, in Cheshire, England, her father, Richard Lyman, was 27 and her mother, Mrs. Richard de Lyman, was 25. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Venables. She died in 1223, in her hometown, at the age of 21."},"et":{"1202–1223":"1202–1223","1198–1250":"1198–1250","1223–1270":"1223–1270","1175–1235":"1175–1235","1177–Female":"1177–Surnud","1215":"1215","1202":"1202","1235":"1235","1223":"1223","1177":"1177","1198":"1198","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Adlington, Lancashire, England":"Adlington, Lancashire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1202–1223":"1202–1223","1198–1250":"1198–1250","1223–1270":"1223–1270","1175–1235":"1175–1235","1177–Female":"1177–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1202":"1202","1235":"1235","1223":"1223","1177":"1177","1198":"1198","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Adlington, Lancashire, England":"Adlington, Lancashire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"1202–1223":"1202–1223","1198–1250":"1198–1250","1223–1270":"1223–1270","1175–1235":"1175–1235","1177–Female":"1177–Décédée","1215":"1215","1202":"1202","1235":"1235","1223":"1223","1177":"1177","1198":"1198","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Adlington, Lancashire, England":"Adlington, Lancashire, Angleterre","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Agnes Lyman est née en 1202, à Cheshire, Angleterre, son père, Richard Lyman, avait 27 ans et sa mère, Mrs. Richard de Lyman, avait 25 ans. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Thomas Venables. Elle est décédée en 1223, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 21 ans."},"de":{"1202–1223":"1202–1223","1198–1250":"1198–1250","1223–1270":"1223–1270","1175–1235":"1175–1235","1177–Female":"1177–Verstorben","1215":"1215","1202":"1202","1235":"1235","1223":"1223","1177":"1177","1198":"1198","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Adlington, Lancashire, England":"Adlington, Lancashire, Eng